Implement aria-current in the MegaNav as an HTML Attribute

03
On this page
  1. 🛠️ Challenge: Implement aria-current in the MegaNav as a DOM Element Attribute
  2. 🛠️ Solution: Implement aria-current in the MegaNav as a DOM Element Attribute
    1. Storing the Current Path in State
    2. Writing a Location Comparison Function
    3. Setting the aria-current Value when Items are Created

We just implemented functionality that sets ariaCurrent for the home page link in header.js as an AOM property. However, this will only work for users who have enabled additional browser configuration.

This was an exercise to experiment with setting an AOM property and seeing it reflected in the DOM. But in order to ensure the functionality works for everyone, we should really implement aria-current as an HTML attribute instead.

🛠️ Challenge: Implement aria-current in the MegaNav as a DOM Element Attribute

Your challenge is to dynamically set aria-current on the list item elements in the MegaNav’s SubNavLinkGroup component located in subnav-link-group.js.

Here is the component source for outputting dynamic groups of anchor links in the MegaNav (so they don’t all have to be hard-coded):

// components/meganav/subnav-link-group.js
const SubNavLinkGroup = ({headerText = '', items = []}) => {
  return (
    <div className="megamenu-submenu-group">
      <h3 className="megamenu-submenu-header">
          {headerText}
      </h3>
      <ul>
      {items.map((item, index) => (
        <li className="megamenu-submenu-link" key={index}>
          <a
            className="nav-link"
            data-testid={`link-${index}`}
            href={item.url}
          >
            {item.name}
          </a>
        </li>
      ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  )
}
// components/meganav/subnav-link-group.js

The process for setting aria-current as an attribute will be similar to what we did in the previous section, with a couple of differences.

A state variable for the currentPathName should be created using React’s useState hook and updated on the page’s first client-side render.

Import useState and initialize this variable by adding the following line to the component above the return statement:

const [currentPathname, setCurrentPathname] = useState(null)
const [currentPathname, setCurrentPathname] = useState(null)

Instead of using the useRef Hook, you will be able to apply the aria-current attribute directly by comparing the anchor item’s URL with the current path.

Write a function that does this comparison. If the paths are the same, set aria-current to page. Otherwise, set it to null.

🛠️ Solution: Implement aria-current in the MegaNav as a DOM Element Attribute

Storing the Current Path in State

With useState imported and a currentPathname variable created, we need a useEffect that will set the current path once when the page first renders.

	useEffect(() => {
    setCurrentPathname(document.location.pathname)
  }, [])

	useEffect(() => {
    setCurrentPathname(document.location.pathname)
  }, [])

Writing a Location Comparison Function

When it comes time to set the value of the aria-current attribute, we need to compare a link item’s URL to the current page’s path. If it’s a match, we’ll return page. Otherwise, we’ll return null.

An if statement inside of a function will get this job done.

	const locationFn = (itemUrl) => {
    if(currentPathname === itemUrl) {
      return 'page'
    } else {
      return null
    }
  }
	const locationFn = (itemUrl) => {
    if(currentPathname === itemUrl) {
      return 'page'
    } else {
      return null
    }
  }

Setting the aria-current Value when Items are Created

We can use React and JSX to run a dynamic expression that outputs a string value for our attribute.

Inside of the items.map() where the links are created, add the aria-current attribute on the <a> tag and set its value to the result of calling locationFn and passing in the current item’s url:

// components/meganav/subnav-link-group.js

  {items.map((item, index) => (
    <li className="megamenu-submenu-link" key={index}>
      <a
        aria-current={locationFn(item.url)}
        className="nav-link"
        data-testid={`link-${index}`}
        href={item.url}
      >
        {item.name}
      </a>
    </li>
  ))}
// components/meganav/subnav-link-group.js

  {items.map((item, index) => (
    <li className="megamenu-submenu-link" key={index}>
      <a
        aria-current={locationFn(item.url)}
        className="nav-link"
        data-testid={`link-${index}`}
        href={item.url}
      >
        {item.name}
      </a>
    </li>
  ))}

Now if we navigate to a matching page in our MegaNav sub-menu, the aria-current attribute will be added to the current page’s entry in the menu.
